AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp;The EU Council adopted the revised Directive on industrial emissions (Ied) and the Regulation on the establishment of an industrial emissions portal (Iep), two complementary legislative acts aimed at regulating and monitoring the environmental impact of industrial activities.
&nbsp;
The new standards will offer better protection of human health and the environment by reducing the harmful emissions of industrial plants, while promoting energy efficiency, circular economy and decarbonization. They will also improve the communication of environmental data by updating the current European register of emissions and transfers of pollutants (E-prtr) in order to create a more complete and integrated industrial emissions portal.
&nbsp;
The Directive on industrial emissions is the main instrument of the EU which regulates pollution caused by industrial plants, including intensive farming. The plants regulated by the existing directive - including power plants, refineries and waste treatment - account for around 40% of greenhouse gas emissions and 20% of air and water pollutants, the Council explains.
&nbsp;
In order to further reduce industrial emissions, the revised Directive includes a greater number of large-scale intensive farms, including pig and poultry farms. Mining activities and large-scale production of batteries are also included: After review by the Commission, the scope may also be extended to industrial minerals.
&nbsp;
Member States shall establish effective, proportionate and dissuasive penalties in the event of failure to comply with the Directive. In case of serious infringements, operators may be required to pay penalties up to at least 3% of their annual turnover in the Union. The Directive also introduces the right for persons whose health has been impaired to seek compensation to those who violate the directive.&nbsp;

