AGI - The EU Council formally adopted the reformed directive on energy efficiency in building which aims to cut greenhouse gas emissions and reduce energy poverty in the EU.
&nbsp;
At present buildings represent more than a third of the EU's greenhouse gas emissions. According to the new rules - the Council explains - by 2030 all new buildings should be buildings with zero emissions, and by 2050 the building heritage of the EU should be transformed into a building heritage with zero emissions.
&nbsp;
For non-residential buildings, the revised Directive introduces minimum energy performance standards ensuring that these buildings do not exceed the maximum specified amount of primary or final energy that they can use for m2 each year. According to the new rules, in 2030 all non-residential buildings will be above 16% of buildings with the worst performance and by 2033 above 26% of buildings with the worst performance in terms of energy performance. This will lead to a gradual elimination of non-residential buildings with the worst performance. Member States may choose to exempte specific buildings from the norms, such as historic buildings, worship sites or buildings owned by the armed forces.
&nbsp;
Member States will also ensure that the average primary energy consumption of residential buildings will be reduced by 16% in 2030 and 20-22% in 2035. At least 55% of the energy reduction will be achieved through the renovation of the most deteriorated buildings, representing 43% of residential buildings with the worst performance. In their renewal efforts, Member States will implement technical assistance and financial support measures, with particular attention to vulnerable families.
&nbsp;
In order to decarbonize the building sector, national plans for building renovation will include a roadmap with the aim of gradually eliminating fossil fuel boilers by 2040.
&nbsp;
The new rules will ensure the installation of suitable solar power plants in new buildings, public buildings and existing non-residential buildings that require a permit. They will also provide sustainable mobility infrastructures, including charging points for electric cars inside or next to buildings, pre-wires or pipelines to accommodate future infrastructure and bicycle parking.
<br The Directive will now be signed and published in the Official Journal of the EU. Member States shall have two years to transpose the provisions of the Directive into their national legislation. The Commission will review the Directive by 2028 in the light of the experience gained and progress made during its implementation. &nbsp;

