AGI - The threats of retaliation from Iran against Israel are causing an increase in tension in the Middle East, while the negotiations for a truce in Gaza are still waiting for answers from the contenders Israel and Hamas to the last proposal of the mediators. The United States, which maintain their support for Israel despite the tensions and polemics between Tel Aviv and Washington, announced the limitation of their diplomatic personnel and members of their families to Israel. In the context of "escalation" with Iran, the American general responsible for the Middle East, Michael Erik Kurilla, is in Israel to discuss with the country's military leadership the "security threat in the region". The German airline Lufthansa has announced a wider suspension of its flights to and from Tehran, "probably until Saturday", just after the increase of tensions between the two Middle Eastern countries.
&nbsp;
<div </div
<br The supreme leader of Iran, the Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, whose country, enemy of Israel, supports Hamas, indicated that Israel will be "punished" after the first April attack in Syria, which destroyed the Iranian consulate in Damascus and caused the death of 16 people, including seven members of the Revolutionary Guard Corps, the ideological army of the Islamic Republic. "If Iran does an attack from its territory, Israel will respond and attack Iran," Israeli Foreign Minister Israel Katz replied in Persian.
&nbsp;
During telephone talks with his German, Australian and British counterparts, the head of Iranian diplomacy, Hossein Amir-Abdollahian, spoke of the "necessity" that Tehran responds to the attack against his consulate in Damascus, trying to "avoid tensions". Iran, said to its Western counterparts, "is not trying to broaden the scope of the war," wrote on X. The White House said it had "adverted" Iran >, while the Secretary of State Antony Blinken spoke on the phone with Chinese, Turkish and Saudi counterparts, inviting them to press on Teheran against any attack against Israel. Russia and Germany, for their part, asked "moderation" to avoid an escalation in the Middle East. "We are in the middle of the war in Gaza, which continues at full pace but we also prepare to face the challenges in other theatres" of operations, said Netanyahu yesterday.
&nbsp;
As regards the negotiations for a ceasefire, there has not been a compromise acceptable to the two parties in conflict. Yesterday, Israel accused Hamas of "turning his back" to a very reasonable offer." The last proposal from Qatar, the United States and Egypt, the countries that make mediators, provides for a 6-week truce and the liberation of 42 of the 130 hostages still held in Gaza in exchange for the release of 8-900 Palestinians in prison and the return home of the inhabitants of the north of the Strip displaced. Hamas instead calls for a definitive truce, the withdrawal of Israeli troops from Gaza, the increase of aid, the return of the displaced and a "serio" agreement of exchange between hostages and prisoners.&nbsp;
